english:
  title: Record of the Ancient Stream
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Yeon is a monk versed in the teachings of the Divine Seal school. His spirit flows naturally, his heart remains serene. He has abandoned the pursuit of gain and fame, dwelling deep in meditative silence—many among the learned of our time hold him in high regard. Now he has hung a tablet inscribed "Ancient Stream" and asked me to write this record.

    I reflect that human nature's goodness is like water's clarity. Though our nature is inherently good, evil arises through desire's enticement. Though water is inherently clear, it becomes murky through pollution. Shed what is evil and preserve what is good—then human nature returns to its source. Remove the turbidity and reveal the clarity—then water fulfills its true form.

    Yet consider the waters of the world: small streams and ponds, great rivers and seas—all are water. Streams and ponds sit low, so filth easily gathers and taints them. Rivers and seas have vast capacity, so they receive all murkiness without protest. Yet neither can achieve perfect clarity. Only the mountain stream achieves this perfection. Its source lies high where filth cannot reach. Its current runs swift so sediment cannot settle. Stone shapes its rapids, sand filters its flow. Though it swells and overflows, rushing swift and violent, plunging into cascades or swirling in pools, flowing straight or twisting through curves, sometimes raging, sometimes hidden, surging in flood or gasping through ice—its transformations are countless, yet its clarity remains unchanged. Day and night, its murmur continues unceasing through ten thousand ages.

    Those who cultivate the Way should draw strength from this. Let the heart be clear, let nature be restored. Hold fast to goodness without wavering. Master Yeon has withdrawn from the world, entering the mountains. Fearing his refuge might lack depth, he built his dwelling by this stream. At dawn he watches its flow; at night he listens to its voice. Each moment he returns to self-examination—his heart becomes clear like the water, his practice unceasing like its course. Heaven's gift of goodness dwells serene within him, flowing naturally through all his actions and silence, speech and stillness. This is why the stream called itself "Ancient."

    As for the Buddhist teachings, I have not yet crossed their waters, so I do not presume to speak of them.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Divine Seal school (神印宗) refers to a Buddhist tradition emphasizing the transmission of enlightenment through direct communion.
  - key: ''
    value: The date "Cycle of the Blue Dragon, tenth month, eighth day" (甲子冬十月甲戌) places this record in 1384.
  - key: ''
    value: Gwon Geun was a leading Neo-Confucian scholar of early Joseon, known for his philosophical writings blending Confucian and Buddhist thought.
